text: The Building Energy Codes Program (BECP) recently conducted a nationwide commercial energy code
label: BODY

text: analysis for the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE). The analysis compares ANSI/ASHRAE/IESNA1 Standard
label: BODY

text: 90.1-2007 with the commercial code in each state as of June 2009. The results are provided in this report in
label: BODY

text: Standard 90.1-2007 was chosen for this analysis because it is the baseline energy standard established in the
label: BODY

text: American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 and the subject of DOE’s forthcoming determination of
label: BODY

text: energy savings for Standard 90.1. An overview of Standard 90.1-2007, as well as a brief comparison to previous
label: BODY

text: versions, is provided as introductory information.
label: BODY

text: States with unique energy codes were not included in the analysis as the codes in these states would be difficult
label: BODY

text: to appropriately compare to Standard 90.1 and most of these states have energy offices that routinely assess
label: BODY

text: their codes against the national codes. In states with codes prior to and including the 2000 IECC or Standard
label: BODY

text: 90.1-1999, those states with no statewide energy code, and home rule states which did not specifically request
label: BODY

text: that another code be used, Standard 90.1-1999 was used as the baseline for comparison.  Standard 90.1-1999
label: BODY

text: was chosen as the default baseline because BECP believes it fairly represents current construction practice in
label: BODY

text: states with older codes or no codes.
label: BODY

text: Three DOE Benchmark buildings were used for the simulation used in this analysis: a medium office building
label: BODY

text: (53,600 ft2), a mid-rise apartment building (33,700 ft2), and a non-refrigerated warehouse (49,500 ft2)—
label: BODY

text: representing the Standard 90.1 nonresidential, residential, and semiheated requirements, respectively. The
label: BODY

text: buildings are described in further detail in the report, and in Appendix A.
label: BODY

text: Locations for the analysis were selected based on obtaining a sample representative of each climate zone in the
label: BODY

text: state, where TMY2 weather file locations existed, making sure to include the state capital. In the absence of a
label: BODY

text: TMY2 weather file for a particular climate zone in a state, a representative location in an adjacent state was
label: BODY

text: used for the purposes of the simulation. These locations, and the full results of each state specific analysis
label: BODY

text: completed by BECP, are provided in the following report.2

text: This report describes the results of a nationwide commercial energy code analysis undertaken by the Building
label: BODY

text: Energy Codes Program (BECP) for the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE).  The task involved comparing each
label: BODY

text: state’s current commercial energy code3 to ANSI/ASHRAE/IESNA4 Standard 90.1-2007 (Standard 90.1-2007).
label: BODY

text: State-specific results are provided in separate chapters.
label: BODY

text: The commercial comparison is made to Standard 90.1-2007 because that is the baseline commercial energy
label: BODY

text: standard established in the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009.  Standard 90.1-2007 will also
label: BODY

text: soon be the subject of DOE’s latest determination of energy savings for Standard 90.1.
label: BODY

text: Standard 90.1-2007 sets requirements for the cost-effective use of energy in commercial buildings.  Certain
label: BODY

text: buildings that have very low energy use, such as buildings with no heating or cooling, are exempt.  Standard
label: BODY

text: 90.1-2007 applies to new buildings and to alterations and additions to existing buildings.
label: BODY

text: Table 1 shows the organization of Standard 90.1-2007.  Most of the actual requirements are contained in
label: BODY

text: Sub-section numbers are standardized across the requirements sections.  For example, sub-section 4 (x.4) is
label: BODY

text: always the Mandatory Requirements.  Table 2 shows the basic organization of the sub-sections used in Sections
label: BODY

text: 5-10, although not all sub-sections are used in every Section.

text: 3.0 Comparison to Previous Versions of Standard 90.1
label: HH1

text: The first Standard 90.1 was published in 1975, with revisions released in 1980, 1989, and 1999.  Standard 90.1
label: BODY

text: was placed under continuous maintenance in 1999 which allowed the Standard to be updated with publication
label: BODY

text: of approved addenda.  Beginning with Standard 90.1-2001, the Standard moved to a three-year publication
label: BODY

text: Substantial revisions to the Standard have occurred since 1989.  One major change was a complete revision of
label: BODY

text: the climate zones in 2004.  These revised climates zones are shown in Figure 1.
label: BODY

text: IMPACTS OF STANDARD 90.1-2007 FOR COMMERCIAL BUILDINGS AT STATE LEVEL
label: BODY

text: Some of the significant requirements in Standard 90.1-2007 include:
label: BODY

text:  Simplified fenestration requirements excluding orientation and window wall ratio
label: BODY

text:  Demand control ventilation requirements for spaces with an occupant density greater than 40 people per
label: BODY

text:  Separate simple and complex mechanical requirements.
label: BODY

text: An energy analysis was conducted comparing each state’s base code to Standard 90.1-2007.  The EnergyPlus
label: BODY

text: software was used to determine the energy impacts.  EnergyPlus was developed by the U.S. Department of
label: BODY

text: States with unique energy codes (i.e., those that do not adopt/amend the International Energy Conservation
label: BODY

text: Code® [IECC] or Standard 90.1) were not included in the analysis.  This decision was made by DOE for two
label: BODY

text: reasons:  1) these states generally have codes that have little resemblance to Standard 90.1, making a thorough
label: BODY

text: comparison beyond the scope of this effort, and 2) most of these states have highly capable energy offices that
label: BODY

text: routinely assess their codes against the national codes.  However, states that were not included in the original
label: BODY

text: analysis may request to be considered for a similar analysis by contacting BECP at techsupport@becp.pnl.gov.
label: BODY

text: In some cases, decisions about base codes needed to be made.  For example, all versions of the IECC include
label: BODY

text: two compliance options for commercial buildings:  the commercial requirements in the IECC and Standard
label: BODY

text: 90.1.  Since there can only be one base code in the analysis, if a state specifically adopts the IECC as its
label: BODY

text: commercial code, the commercial requirements from the applicable IECC were used in the analysis.  There are
label: BODY

text: several states with older commercial codes6.  For states with codes prior to and including the 2000 IECC or
label: BODY

text: Standard 90.1-1999, Standard 90.1-1999 was used as the base code.
label: BODY

text: Standard 90.1-1999 was chosen as the baseline construction for states with older codes because it has been
label: BODY

text: around long enough (about 10 years) to allow many of the concepts and requirements embodied in it to become
label: BODY

text: common practice in the construction industry.  Standard 90.1-1999 also represents a major change in ASHRAE
label: BODY

text: standards, coming ten years after the previous version of Standard 90.1.  Standard 90.1-1999 is old enough that
label: BODY

text: states considering adoption of Standard 90.1-2007 will still see significant savings, but not so old that states will
label: BODY

text: be misled by the savings shown in this report.  Keeping with the concept of Standard 90.1-1999 as “common
label: BODY

text: practice” in the construction industry, Standard 90.1-1999 was also used as the base code for states with no
label: BODY

text: state-wide commercial energy code.  Some home rule states7 requested a specific code be used in the analysis;
label: BODY

text: for all other home rule states Standard 90.1-1999 was used as the base code.
label: BODY

text: Three DOE Benchmark buildings8 were used for the simulation:  a medium office building, a mid-rise
label: BODY

text: apartment building, and a non-refrigerated warehouse (semiheated).  These three building types represent the
label: BODY

text: Standard 90.1 nonresidential, residential, and semiheated requirements, respectively.  For states that have
label: BODY

text: adopted a newer version of Standard 90.1 (1999 or later), the three types of envelope requirements were
label: BODY

text: compared directly.  For states that have adopted a version of the IECC that contains only a single set of
label: BODY

text: commercial envelope requirements (any version prior to the 2009 IECC), the medium office and mid-rise
label: BODY

text: apartment buildings were modeled using the single set of IECC requirements.  The warehouse building was
label: BODY

text: modeled using the semiheated envelope requirements from the reference standard version of Standard 90.1
label: BODY

text: incorporated in the version of the IECC under consideration.  DOE assumes that any designer of a warehouse
label: BODY

text: that would truly be considered semiheated within Standard 90.1 would be motivated to use the Standard 90.1
label: BODY

text: semiheated envelope requirements as allowed by the IECC.
label: BODY

text: Use of the IECC requirements for semiheated values in a comparison with Standard 90.1-2007 would lead to
label: BODY

text: the awkward conclusion that the IECC is more stringent.  This is true in the sense that use of more insulation in
label: BODY

text: semiheated buildings will save some energy.  However, because Standard 90.1-2007 is the designated
label: BODY

text: comparison and it has separate semiheated envelope requirements, DOE chose to compare those semiheated
label: BODY

text: requirements in the ASHRAE reference standard to the IECC.
label: BODY

text: The medium office has a gross area of 53,600 ft2, three floors, and a window-to-wall ratio (WWR) of 33%.  The
label: BODY

text: HVAC systems are assumed to be a gas furnace and a packaged DX unit.  The walls are modeled as steel frame
label: BODY

text: walls, and the roof as insulation entirely above deck.
label: BODY

text: The mid-rise apartment building has a gross area of 33,700 ft2, four floors, and a WWR of 15%.  The assumed
label: BODY

text: heating system is a gas furnace, with one split DX system assumed to provide cooling for each apartment.  The
label: BODY

text: walls are modeled as steel frame walls, and the roof as insulation entirely above deck.
label: BODY

text: The semiheated warehouse has a gross area of 49,500 ft2, one floor, and no windows in the storage area.
label: BODY

text: Limited heating is provided by unit heaters and no cooling is provided.  The walls and roof are modeled as

label: BODY
